{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501896","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501896"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:35:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:35:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1804"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1804","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1804"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.39,0.1,0.03,0.01,0.48]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1804"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42547"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1804","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1804"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1804"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27511"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"1217"},{"type":"tags","id":"1239"},{"type":"tags","id":"2125"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1340"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12332"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42547","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/42547"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 20-year-old man presents with testicular pain which has been ongoing since a groin injury during a soccer match two days ago. The pain has not improved with regular analgesia and ice packs applied to the groin. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, the left testis is swollen, tender on palpation and there is a palpably thickened cord. There is no overlying erythema of the skin. The testis do not transilluminate. An ultrasound examination shows a small quantity (\u0026lt;10ml) of blood within the tunica vaginalis and a 1 cm tear in the tunica albuginea.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management approach?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Conservative management","Aspiration","Empirical antibiotics","Insertion of indwelling catheter","Surgical exploration"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case describes a case of a ruptured testis. Testicular rupture can occur after blunt trauma to the testis. Patients often present with pain and swelling. The definition of a ruptured testis includes a tear in the tunica albuginea, such as in this case. Without a tear, it might have been quite appropriate to recommend \u003Cstrong\u003Econservative management \u003C/strong\u003Econsisting of bed rest, a scrotal support and ice packs, but with this tear \u003Cstrong\u003Esurgical exploration\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate course of action. The aim of surgery is to excise any devitalised tissue, contain any bleeding and to repair the tunica albuginea. Without decompression, the viability of the testis is in jeopardy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspiration\u003C/strong\u003E would not be an appropriate course of action in this case. Additionally, \u003Cstrong\u003Eempirical antibiotics \u003C/strong\u003Emay be considered if it were more suggestive of epididymitis however this is more likely to present over a longer duration, with fever and potentially dysuria or frequency. There is no description in the stem of issues with urination or obstruction, hence\u003Cstrong\u003E inserting an indwelling catheter\u003C/strong\u003E would not be the most appropriate management option.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA good differential diagnosis for this case is testicular torsion, which would likely produce similar excruciating pain. However, most patients with torsion present earlier because of the intensity of their symptoms (pain, nausea and potentially vomiting). Torsion would also require urgent surgical exploration - and ultrasonography would only be undertaken if it did not delay surgery. If performed, ultrasound might show the torsion itself and an absent or diminished blood flow to the testicle.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Testicular rupture occurs when there is a tear in the tunica albuginea"],"references":["McConaghy JR, Panchal B. Epididymitis: An Overview. Am Fam Physician. 2016 Nov 1;94(9):723-726. Available at: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2016/1101/p723.html","Holliday TL, Robinson KS, Dorinzi N, Vucelik AW, Setzer EL, Williams DL, et al. Testicular Rupture: A Tough Nut to Crack. Clin Pract Cases Emerg Med. 2017;1(3):221-224. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5965175/#:~:text=The%20findings%20of%20testicular%20rupture,surgery%2C%20which%20should%20improve%20outcomes."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27511"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1804"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27511","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/27511"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-02-12T10:34:56+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-02-12T10:34:56+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1804"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42547"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji"